# Core Explanations

## Summary Statistics — The Basics

Before you build any machine learning model, you must first **understand your data**.
This is called **Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)**.

The first step is looking at **summary statistics** for each column.

In R, a single command gives you everything:
```r
summary(iris[, -5])  # -5 means "exclude column 5" (which is the Species label)
```

This gives you for each column:
- **Min** — the smallest value
- **1st Quartile (Q1)** — 25% of data is below this
- **Median** — the middle value (50% below, 50% above)
- **Mean** — the mathematical average
- **3rd Quartile (Q3)** — 75% of data is below this
- **Max** — the largest value

---

## Mean vs Median — Which One to Use?

This is one of the most important concepts in Week 2.

**Mean** = Add all values together, divide by how many there are.

**Median** = Sort all values from smallest to largest, pick the one in the middle.

> 💡 **Salary Example:**
> Imagine a room of 10 people earning between €25,000 and €60,000.
> Their average salary (mean) = €38,000. Makes sense!
>
> Now a billionaire walks in. His salary is €500,000,000.
> The new mean = about €50,000,000. This is completely misleading — nobody in the room earns close to that!
> The **median** barely changes — it still reflects the "typical" person in the room.

**Key rule:**

| Situation | Use This |
|-----------|----------|
| Data is fairly symmetric (bell-shaped) | **Mean** is fine |
| Data has outliers or is skewed | **Median** is better |

> 💡 **Real example from class:** The COVID-19 death statistics.
> If median age of COVID death = 60, it means 50% of deaths were people under 60, and 50% over 60.
> That is much more informative than reporting an average that is distorted by extreme ages.

