## The Three Univariate Plots

**Univariate** means looking at **one column at a time**.
These three plots all show the same information but in different ways:

### Histogram

A bar chart that shows **how many values** fall in each range.

- The x-axis is the value (e.g., age, salary, petal length)
- The y-axis is the count (how many rows have that value)
- Useful for seeing the **shape** of the distribution

> 💡 **What to look for:** Is there one peak, two peaks, or a long tail on one side?

### Density Plot

Like a histogram, but drawn as a **smooth curve** instead of bars.

- Easier to see the shape of the distribution
- Same information as a histogram, just a smoother version

### Boxplot

The most **information-rich** of the three — but the hardest for non-statisticians to read.

```
          |                      |
   -------|==========|===========|----------  ●  (outlier)
          |    Q1    | Median |  Q3   |
          |          |        |       |
          ↑                           ↑
        Q1 - 1.5*IQR              Q3 + 1.5*IQR
        (lower "whisker")         (upper "whisker")
```

A boxplot shows:
- The **box** = the interquartile range (Q1 to Q3) — the middle 50% of data
- The **line inside the box** = the median
- The **dot inside the box** (in some plots) = the mean
- The **whiskers** = data extending to Q1 − 1.5×IQR and Q3 + 1.5×IQR
- The **dots outside the whiskers** = outliers

> ⚠️ **Professor's advice:**
> Boxplots are very useful for YOU as a data scientist to understand the data.
> But **do not show them to business users** — they do not understand them!
> Use simpler charts (bar charts, line charts) for presentations to non-technical people.

