## The Normal Distribution (Bell Curve)

The **normal distribution** is the most common distribution in nature.

- Most values are **near the average** (the middle)
- Fewer values are at the extremes (the tails)
- It looks like a bell — highest in the middle, tapering off on both sides

```
        *
       ***
      *****
     *******
    *********
   ***********
  *************
```

**Why does this matter for machine learning?**

Many ML algorithms make a **hidden assumption** that your data follows a normal distribution.
If your data is skewed, these algorithms may not work as well — or give wrong results.

> 💡 **When mean ≈ median:** the data is approximately normal.
> **When mean ≠ median by a lot:** the data is likely skewed.

---

## Skewed Data

**Skewed data** is data that does NOT follow the normal distribution.
The curve is shifted or stretched to one side.

### Right-Skewed (Positive Skew)

The long tail is on the **right** side. Most values are small, but a few are very large.

```
    **
   ****
  ******
 **********_________
```

- **Mean > Median** (the mean is pulled up by the large values)
- Examples: income, house prices, average spend per customer, animal body weights

### Left-Skewed (Negative Skew)

The long tail is on the **left** side. Most values are large, but a few are very small.

- **Mean < Median**

> 💡 **How to spot skew:**
> In a histogram or density plot, look at which side has the longer tail.
> In a boxplot, if the median line is not centred in the box, the data is skewed.
> If the mean (blue line) and median (green line) are far apart → skewed!

---

## How to Fix Skewed Data — Log Transformation

Many machine learning algorithms work better when data is approximately normally distributed.
A simple fix for right-skewed data is the **log transformation**.

```r
mammals$log_body_wt  <- log(mammals$body_wt)   # transform body weight
mammals$log_brain_wt <- log(mammals$brain_wt)  # transform brain weight
```

**Before log transform:** Data is very skewed (a few huge mammals like elephants distort everything)

**After log transform:** Data looks much more like a bell curve — and the model performs much better!

> 💡 **Mammals Example from class:**
> The professor showed the `mammals` dataset which has `body_wt` and `brain_wt`.
> Most mammals are small (mice, rabbits), but elephants are enormous outliers.
>
> Without log transform: R² = 0.87 (decent but not great)
> With log transform: R² = 0.92 (much better — 35% improvement!)
>
> This shows the power of a simple transformation.

> ⚠️ **Important rule on outliers:**
> Don't just delete outliers because they look strange!
> Ask yourself: *"Is this a real value that could appear in my future data?"*
> The elephants are real large mammals. If you delete them and your model later sees a hippo,
> it will fail. Keep them — and transform the data instead.

