## Bimodal Distribution — A Red Flag

A **bimodal distribution** has **two peaks** in the histogram or density plot.

```
  *          *
 ***        ***
*****      *****
```

This is a **warning signal**. It usually means one of two things:

1. **Two different groups** are mixed in your data (e.g., heights of men and women combined into one column)
2. **Data was recorded incorrectly** or there is something unusual happening

> 💡 **Iris Dataset Example:**
> When you plot `Petal.Length` for the Iris dataset, you see two peaks.
> Why? Because **Setosa flowers** have very small petals (peak on the left),
> while **Versicolor and Virginica** have much larger petals (peak on the right).
>
> This tells you: *"These species are very different — the model should find it easy to separate them!"*
> It also means: you should consider treating them as different sub-groups.

