# Summary Points

- **Mean** is the average. **Median** is the middle value. Use **median** when data is skewed or has outliers.
- **Quartiles** divide sorted data into 4 equal groups. **IQR** = Q3 − Q1 (the range of the middle 50%).
- **Histogram** = bar chart of frequencies. **Density plot** = smooth version of histogram. **Boxplot** = shows IQR, median, mean, and outliers.
- A **boxplot** is useful for data scientists but **confusing for business users** — avoid in presentations.
- The **normal distribution** (bell curve) is the ideal shape for most ML algorithms. Many algorithms assume your data is normally distributed.
- **Skewed data** has a long tail on one side. The mean and median will be far apart.
- Use the **log transformation** to convert right-skewed data into a more normal shape.
- A **bimodal distribution** (two peaks) is a red flag — it means two different groups may be mixed in your data.
- **Scatter plots** show the relationship between two columns. Look for diagonal patterns.
- **Correlation** ranges from -1 to +1. Near ±1 = strong relationship. Near 0 = weak/none.
- **`ggpairs()`** from the GGally library is your best friend for data exploration — it shows everything at once.
- **Always plot your data BEFORE modelling.** Exploratory analysis helps you find problems and opportunities.
- Do not delete outliers just because they look unusual. Ask: *"Is this a real value that could happen in future?"*

